issue.title: Change invite mode with tootctl

labels.name: suggestion
labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

A mastodon instance can have different invite modes (from "nobody can invite" to "all users" with separate settings for "just mods" and "just admins"). However, there isn't a way to change the invite mode with `tootctl` or any other way except with the admin interface.

### Motivation

Related to #19786, we're currently scripting our invite limits, but we'd like to do so in a way that is supported by mastodon, and with as little of direct writes to the DB as possible.

issue.title: Limit registrations per day / registration quotas

labels.name: suggestion
labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

Add a setting of max users to join per day (or other intervals, but I think days are a good first go). Once that many users have joined in a day, close registrations entirely until the next day.

### Motivation

We're seeing a rise in user registrations even across invite-only instances. It would be nice to permit users to invite others, while also keeping the growth at a level we can sustain. We're currently handling this with a cronjob and a custom script, but literally anything else would be preferable!

Instance growth is a problem all over the Fediverse, and in particular on Mastodon with its local timeline.

This feature would also have the advantage of allowing users to create invites even while invites can currently not be used (because the daily quota has been reached).

issue.title: Show moderation actions in moderator view of a user

labels.name: suggestion
labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

As a moderator, viewing a user's profile (in `/admin/accounts/:id`) can be very confusing because not all moderator actions taken are visible.

### Motivation

For example, warning or limiting a user shows up in the "Previous strikes" section, but *un*limiting a user does not show up. So you could have a user who is currently not limited, and you'd see when they were originally limited, but you'd have no way (apart from going through every page of the moderator audit log and searching for their name!) to see when the limit action was revoked.

issue.title: Installation via pip broken due to missing __init__.py
issue.body:
I have struggled to install the updated version of the plugin using pip for a while now and found the problem today:

In the setup.py the packages to be installed are found using `find_packages()` from `setuptools`, which seems to be the preferred version of doing things, but returns an empty list, when there is no `__inity__.py` present in the module folder. Simply adding an empty file named `__init__.py` in the module folder resolved the issue for me.
References:
https://github.com/pretalx/pretalx-public-voting/blob/b908b61992b94b9c3312221431e399e9fd3e291d/setup.py#L35
https://stackoverflow.com/a/64404115

issue.title: Show announcement reactions in admin interface

labels.name: suggestion
labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

Server-wide announcements can receive emoji reactions from users. It would be nice to see those reactions in the administration interface, particularly when an announcement is not live anymore.

### Motivation

Announcement reactions are a really cool way to see the mood on a server at the time of an announcment. However, once the announcement is not live anymore, it's not possible to see the reactions anymore, even though they are saved. It would be really nice to just add a list of emoji + reaction count in the interface at `/admin/announcements/:id/edit`, so admins could look back to see reactions after the fact!

issue.title: Fix remaining draft proposal issues
issue.body:
Draft proposals as per #672 have been implemented in #1373, but there are a few remaining sub-features that need to be implemented before we can release. (The semi-done feature was merged to facilitate early testing).

- [ ] **Send emails to users with drafts.** These emails are intended as reminders sent by the organisers. The tricky bit is that organisers are not meant to know who has unsubmitted drafts lying around, which has a bunch of unfortunate implications:
	- [ ] Drafts cannot be used to generate email previews
	- [ ] Emails to users with drafts have to either be sent immediately, **or** be hidden in the outbox (not sure which is worse)
	- [ ] Emails to users with drafts must not show up in any history, including the action log and the list of emails shown on a user's profile. We'll probably want a `QueuedMail.private` or `QueuedMail.hidden` flag here
- [ ] Discard drafts: users should be allowed to discard/remove drafts, including after the CfP has closed
- [ ] Currently, mandatory profile information and questions can remain unanswered. We need to somehow check for those, and require the user to update their profile page before returning to finalise the draft.

issue.body:
This is an issue that is well-suited for external contributors – let me know if I can be of any help, either via this issue or via support@pretalx.com.

## What this is about

Submitters might not be ready to finish their proposal at submission time, or might want to pencil in details later. Offering a draft status would allow them to fill in what they can now.

## How to get started

First of all, leave a comment on this issue to make sure nobody else starts working on this issue at the same time!

Next, you need pretalx running locally on your machine. First, [fork](https://github.com/pretalx/pretalx/fork) the repository to your own GitHub account. Then clone it locally (or [set it as your remote](https://help.github.com/articles/configuring-a-remote-for-a-fork/) if you already cloned it earlier)

Follow the [developer setup guide](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/setup.html), and then play around with pretalx a bit.
Have a look at the places impacting this issue. Look at the code responsible for the issues (searching for relevant words or files should help you find your way around). We have an explanation of our [code structure](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/concepts.html) and the actual [data models](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/interfaces/models.html).


## How to do this

Make yourself familiar with the `Submission` model. You'll have to add a new `SubmissionState` and exclude it in the default model manager and in the `all_objects` manager, to make sure it shows up nowhere except for the person creating the submission.

These are additional considerations you should think about – but if some of these seem like too much, do some of the work first, open a PR, and we'll take it from there!

### Clear UI

Switching to a draft status should be possible at any point during the workflow, so there needs to be a good and visible switch/button/… to do that. **Switching back cannot be as easy though**, since it requires form validation to run.

It must be very visible at all times if a proposal is edited in draft status.

### Form validation

It would be fair or even expected to disable form validation at this point – but part of the validation (particularly the length and format restrictions) take place client side via HTML attributes. We could remove those via JavaScript (but note that we have successfully avoided solutions requiring JavaScript so far).

All submission forms (including the already heavily meta-programmed question forms) would need to accept one more flag to turn validation on or off.

### Reminders

Submitters should be reminded about pending draft proposals at a (configurable? maybe not.) interval before the CfP closes. Note that different CfP deadlines for different submission types or tracks need to be respected here!

Submitters need to be able to opt out of the reminder, so this will need to be a per-permission flag. (Which is neat, since this can be useful on non-draft proposals, too.)

### Privacy

It needs to be clear that organisers will not be able to see, or review, or comment on draft proposals. Draft proposals should only be visible to the author(s) *and* on the review view, which allows the submission to be shared with people who do not have an account.

## Submit the PR

There are a number of tutorials on the Pull Request workflow online, for example this [short version](https://guides.github.com/introduction/flow/) by GitHub itself and this [more in-depth tutorial](https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-create-a-pull-request-on-github).

Remember to provide documentation and tests, if applicable. Run the tests before opening your PR, including style checks. We have a [contribution guide](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/contributing.html), which ought to prove helpful at this stage.

issue.body:
### Pitch

A mastodon instance can have different invite modes (from "nobody can invite" to "all users" with separate settings for "just mods" and "just admins"). However, there isn't a way to change the invite mode with `tootctl` or any other way except with the admin interface.

### Motivation

Related to #19786, we're currently scripting our invite limits, but we'd like to do so in a way that is supported by mastodon, and with as little of direct writes to the DB as possible.

issue.title: Limit registrations per day / registration quotas

labels.name: suggestion
labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

Add a setting of max users to join per day (or other intervals, but I think days are a good first go). Once that many users have joined in a day, close registrations entirely until the next day.

### Motivation

We're seeing a rise in user registrations even across invite-only instances. It would be nice to permit users to invite others, while also keeping the growth at a level we can sustain. We're currently handling this with a cronjob and a custom script, but literally anything else would be preferable!

Instance growth is a problem all over the Fediverse, and in particular on Mastodon with its local timeline.

This feature would also have the advantage of allowing users to create invites even while invites can currently not be used (because the daily quota has been reached).

labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

As a moderator, viewing a user's profile (in `/admin/accounts/:id`) can be very confusing because not all moderator actions taken are visible.

### Motivation

For example, warning or limiting a user shows up in the "Previous strikes" section, but *un*limiting a user does not show up. So you could have a user who is currently not limited, and you'd see when they were originally limited, but you'd have no way (apart from going through every page of the moderator audit log and searching for their name!) to see when the limit action was revoked.

issue.title: Installation via pip broken due to missing __init__.py
issue.body:
I have struggled to install the updated version of the plugin using pip for a while now and found the problem today:

In the setup.py the packages to be installed are found using `find_packages()` from `setuptools`, which seems to be the preferred version of doing things, but returns an empty list, when there is no `__inity__.py` present in the module folder. Simply adding an empty file named `__init__.py` in the module folder resolved the issue for me.
References:
https://github.com/pretalx/pretalx-public-voting/blob/b908b61992b94b9c3312221431e399e9fd3e291d/setup.py#L35
https://stackoverflow.com/a/64404115

issue.title: Show announcement reactions in admin interface

labels.name: suggestion
labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

Server-wide announcements can receive emoji reactions from users. It would be nice to see those reactions in the administration interface, particularly when an announcement is not live anymore.

### Motivation

Announcement reactions are a really cool way to see the mood on a server at the time of an announcment. However, once the announcement is not live anymore, it's not possible to see the reactions anymore, even though they are saved. It would be really nice to just add a list of emoji + reaction count in the interface at `/admin/announcements/:id/edit`, so admins could look back to see reactions after the fact!

issue.title: Fix remaining draft proposal issues
issue.body:
Draft proposals as per #672 have been implemented in #1373, but there are a few remaining sub-features that need to be implemented before we can release. (The semi-done feature was merged to facilitate early testing).

- [ ] **Send emails to users with drafts.** These emails are intended as reminders sent by the organisers. The tricky bit is that organisers are not meant to know who has unsubmitted drafts lying around, which has a bunch of unfortunate implications:
	- [ ] Drafts cannot be used to generate email previews
	- [ ] Emails to users with drafts have to either be sent immediately, **or** be hidden in the outbox (not sure which is worse)
	- [ ] Emails to users with drafts must not show up in any history, including the action log and the list of emails shown on a user's profile. We'll probably want a `QueuedMail.private` or `QueuedMail.hidden` flag here
- [ ] Discard drafts: users should be allowed to discard/remove drafts, including after the CfP has closed
- [ ] Currently, mandatory profile information and questions can remain unanswered. We need to somehow check for those, and require the user to update their profile page before returning to finalise the draft.

issue.body:
This is an issue that is well-suited for external contributors – let me know if I can be of any help, either via this issue or via support@pretalx.com.

## What this is about

Submitters might not be ready to finish their proposal at submission time, or might want to pencil in details later. Offering a draft status would allow them to fill in what they can now.

## How to get started

First of all, leave a comment on this issue to make sure nobody else starts working on this issue at the same time!

Next, you need pretalx running locally on your machine. First, [fork](https://github.com/pretalx/pretalx/fork) the repository to your own GitHub account. Then clone it locally (or [set it as your remote](https://help.github.com/articles/configuring-a-remote-for-a-fork/) if you already cloned it earlier)

Follow the [developer setup guide](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/setup.html), and then play around with pretalx a bit.
Have a look at the places impacting this issue. Look at the code responsible for the issues (searching for relevant words or files should help you find your way around). We have an explanation of our [code structure](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/concepts.html) and the actual [data models](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/interfaces/models.html).


## How to do this

Make yourself familiar with the `Submission` model. You'll have to add a new `SubmissionState` and exclude it in the default model manager and in the `all_objects` manager, to make sure it shows up nowhere except for the person creating the submission.

These are additional considerations you should think about – but if some of these seem like too much, do some of the work first, open a PR, and we'll take it from there!

### Clear UI

Switching to a draft status should be possible at any point during the workflow, so there needs to be a good and visible switch/button/… to do that. **Switching back cannot be as easy though**, since it requires form validation to run.

It must be very visible at all times if a proposal is edited in draft status.

### Form validation

It would be fair or even expected to disable form validation at this point – but part of the validation (particularly the length and format restrictions) take place client side via HTML attributes. We could remove those via JavaScript (but note that we have successfully avoided solutions requiring JavaScript so far).

All submission forms (including the already heavily meta-programmed question forms) would need to accept one more flag to turn validation on or off.

### Reminders

Submitters should be reminded about pending draft proposals at a (configurable? maybe not.) interval before the CfP closes. Note that different CfP deadlines for different submission types or tracks need to be respected here!

Submitters need to be able to opt out of the reminder, so this will need to be a per-permission flag. (Which is neat, since this can be useful on non-draft proposals, too.)

### Privacy

It needs to be clear that organisers will not be able to see, or review, or comment on draft proposals. Draft proposals should only be visible to the author(s) *and* on the review view, which allows the submission to be shared with people who do not have an account.

## Submit the PR

There are a number of tutorials on the Pull Request workflow online, for example this [short version](https://guides.github.com/introduction/flow/) by GitHub itself and this [more in-depth tutorial](https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-create-a-pull-request-on-github).

Remember to provide documentation and tests, if applicable. Run the tests before opening your PR, including style checks. We have a [contribution guide](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/contributing.html), which ought to prove helpful at this stage.

labels.name: suggestion
labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

A mastodon instance can have different invite modes (from "nobody can invite" to "all users" with separate settings for "just mods" and "just admins"). However, there isn't a way to change the invite mode with `tootctl` or any other way except with the admin interface.

### Motivation

Related to #19786, we're currently scripting our invite limits, but we'd like to do so in a way that is supported by mastodon, and with as little of direct writes to the DB as possible.

issue.title: Limit registrations per day / registration quotas

labels.name: suggestion
labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

Add a setting of max users to join per day (or other intervals, but I think days are a good first go). Once that many users have joined in a day, close registrations entirely until the next day.

### Motivation

We're seeing a rise in user registrations even across invite-only instances. It would be nice to permit users to invite others, while also keeping the growth at a level we can sustain. We're currently handling this with a cronjob and a custom script, but literally anything else would be preferable!

Instance growth is a problem all over the Fediverse, and in particular on Mastodon with its local timeline.

This feature would also have the advantage of allowing users to create invites even while invites can currently not be used (because the daily quota has been reached).

issue.title: Show moderation actions in moderator view of a user

labels.name: suggestion
labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

As a moderator, viewing a user's profile (in `/admin/accounts/:id`) can be very confusing because not all moderator actions taken are visible.

### Motivation

For example, warning or limiting a user shows up in the "Previous strikes" section, but *un*limiting a user does not show up. So you could have a user who is currently not limited, and you'd see when they were originally limited, but you'd have no way (apart from going through every page of the moderator audit log and searching for their name!) to see when the limit action was revoked.

issue.title: Installation via pip broken due to missing __init__.py
issue.body:
I have struggled to install the updated version of the plugin using pip for a while now and found the problem today:

In the setup.py the packages to be installed are found using `find_packages()` from `setuptools`, which seems to be the preferred version of doing things, but returns an empty list, when there is no `__inity__.py` present in the module folder. Simply adding an empty file named `__init__.py` in the module folder resolved the issue for me.
References:
https://github.com/pretalx/pretalx-public-voting/blob/b908b61992b94b9c3312221431e399e9fd3e291d/setup.py#L35
https://stackoverflow.com/a/64404115

issue.title: Show announcement reactions in admin interface

labels.name: suggestion
labels.description: Feature suggestion

issue.body:
### Pitch

Server-wide announcements can receive emoji reactions from users. It would be nice to see those reactions in the administration interface, particularly when an announcement is not live anymore.

### Motivation

Announcement reactions are a really cool way to see the mood on a server at the time of an announcment. However, once the announcement is not live anymore, it's not possible to see the reactions anymore, even though they are saved. It would be really nice to just add a list of emoji + reaction count in the interface at `/admin/announcements/:id/edit`, so admins could look back to see reactions after the fact!

issue.title: Fix remaining draft proposal issues
issue.body:
Draft proposals as per #672 have been implemented in #1373, but there are a few remaining sub-features that need to be implemented before we can release. (The semi-done feature was merged to facilitate early testing).

- [ ] **Send emails to users with drafts.** These emails are intended as reminders sent by the organisers. The tricky bit is that organisers are not meant to know who has unsubmitted drafts lying around, which has a bunch of unfortunate implications:
	- [ ] Drafts cannot be used to generate email previews
	- [ ] Emails to users with drafts have to either be sent immediately, **or** be hidden in the outbox (not sure which is worse)
	- [ ] Emails to users with drafts must not show up in any history, including the action log and the list of emails shown on a user's profile. We'll probably want a `QueuedMail.private` or `QueuedMail.hidden` flag here
- [ ] Discard drafts: users should be allowed to discard/remove drafts, including after the CfP has closed
- [ ] Currently, mandatory profile information and questions can remain unanswered. We need to somehow check for those, and require the user to update their profile page before returning to finalise the draft.

issue.body:
This is an issue that is well-suited for external contributors – let me know if I can be of any help, either via this issue or via support@pretalx.com.

## What this is about

Submitters might not be ready to finish their proposal at submission time, or might want to pencil in details later. Offering a draft status would allow them to fill in what they can now.

## How to get started

First of all, leave a comment on this issue to make sure nobody else starts working on this issue at the same time!

Next, you need pretalx running locally on your machine. First, [fork](https://github.com/pretalx/pretalx/fork) the repository to your own GitHub account. Then clone it locally (or [set it as your remote](https://help.github.com/articles/configuring-a-remote-for-a-fork/) if you already cloned it earlier)

Follow the [developer setup guide](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/setup.html), and then play around with pretalx a bit.
Have a look at the places impacting this issue. Look at the code responsible for the issues (searching for relevant words or files should help you find your way around). We have an explanation of our [code structure](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/concepts.html) and the actual [data models](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/interfaces/models.html).


## How to do this

Make yourself familiar with the `Submission` model. You'll have to add a new `SubmissionState` and exclude it in the default model manager and in the `all_objects` manager, to make sure it shows up nowhere except for the person creating the submission.

These are additional considerations you should think about – but if some of these seem like too much, do some of the work first, open a PR, and we'll take it from there!

### Clear UI

Switching to a draft status should be possible at any point during the workflow, so there needs to be a good and visible switch/button/… to do that. **Switching back cannot be as easy though**, since it requires form validation to run.

It must be very visible at all times if a proposal is edited in draft status.

### Form validation

It would be fair or even expected to disable form validation at this point – but part of the validation (particularly the length and format restrictions) take place client side via HTML attributes. We could remove those via JavaScript (but note that we have successfully avoided solutions requiring JavaScript so far).

All submission forms (including the already heavily meta-programmed question forms) would need to accept one more flag to turn validation on or off.

### Reminders

Submitters should be reminded about pending draft proposals at a (configurable? maybe not.) interval before the CfP closes. Note that different CfP deadlines for different submission types or tracks need to be respected here!

Submitters need to be able to opt out of the reminder, so this will need to be a per-permission flag. (Which is neat, since this can be useful on non-draft proposals, too.)

### Privacy

It needs to be clear that organisers will not be able to see, or review, or comment on draft proposals. Draft proposals should only be visible to the author(s) *and* on the review view, which allows the submission to be shared with people who do not have an account.

## Submit the PR

There are a number of tutorials on the Pull Request workflow online, for example this [short version](https://guides.github.com/introduction/flow/) by GitHub itself and this [more in-depth tutorial](https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-create-a-pull-request-on-github).

Remember to provide documentation and tests, if applicable. Run the tests before opening your PR, including style checks. We have a [contribution guide](https://docs.pretalx.org/en/latest/developer/contributing.html), which ought to prove helpful at this stage.
